    <!-- Body -->
    <article class="article-body">

        <p>
            Most rental listings look the same: a bullet list of bedrooms and bathrooms, a vague sentence about the neighborhood, and a phone number. And then landlords wonder why their inbox is quiet.
        </p>
        <p>
            The truth is, <strong>your listing is your first showing.</strong> Before a prospective tenant ever steps foot in your property, they've already decided whether it's worth a call based on 30 seconds of reading. A weak listing loses that decision every time.
        </p>
        <p>
            Here's a step-by-step framework for writing rental listing copy that attracts quality tenants — and fills vacancies faster.
        </p>

        <h2>1. Lead with the lifestyle, not the specs</h2>
        <p>
            Every listing starts with bedrooms and bathrooms. Yours shouldn't. Features are table stakes — tenants assume a 2-bedroom apartment has two bedrooms. What they're actually searching for is a <em>life they want to live.</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            Instead of opening with:
        </p>
        <div class="article-callout">
            <p>"2BR/1BA apartment available June 1st. 850 sq ft. Laundry in building."</p>
        </div>
        <p>Try leading with:</p>
        <div class="article-callout">
            <p>"Wake up a five-minute walk from the farmer's market, grab a coffee at the corner café, and be on the highway in under 10 minutes. This bright 2-bedroom apartment puts the best of the neighborhood at your door."</p>
        </div>
        <p>
            You can include the specs — but lead with the experience. Emotion drives the call, logic justifies it.
        </p>

        <h2>2. Write a headline that stops the scroll</h2>
        <p>
            On platforms like Zillow and Apartments.com, your headline competes with dozens of listings on the same page. A generic headline like "Nice 2BR in good location" is invisible.
        </p>
        <p>Good headlines follow one of three formulas:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Highlight the #1 feature:</strong> "Sunlit 2BR with Private Rooftop Deck — No Pet Fees"</li>
            <li><strong>Call out the ideal tenant:</strong> "Remote Worker's Dream: Fast WiFi, Dedicated Office, Quiet Block"</li>
            <li><strong>Lead with the neighborhood:</strong> "Steps from Whole Foods & the Metro — Renovated 1BR Available Now"</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Write 2–3 headline options and test them. Small word changes can significantly change click-through rates.
        </p>

        <h2>3. Structure your description for skimmers</h2>
        <p>
            Tenants don't read listings — they scan them. Structure your description so the most important information is impossible to miss.
        </p>
        <p>A proven structure:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Opening hook</strong> (1–2 sentences) — lifestyle or standout feature</li>
            <li><strong>Property highlights</strong> (3–5 bullet points) — the best amenities</li>
            <li><strong>Neighborhood context</strong> (2–3 sentences) — walkability, transit, nearby spots</li>
            <li><strong>Practical details</strong> — rent, availability, lease terms, pet policy</li>
            <li><strong>Call to action</strong> — clear next step ("Schedule a tour at the link below")</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
            Keep the whole description under 300 words. Longer is not better — it's a signal that you don't know what matters.
        </p>

        <h2>4. Be specific about amenities</h2>
        <p>
            "Updated kitchen" means nothing. "Quartz countertops, stainless steel appliances, and a gas range" means something. Specificity builds credibility and paints a picture.
        </p>
        <p>Go through each room and ask: what is the <em>one specific detail</em> that makes this room worth mentioning? Then write that detail, not a generic category.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Instead of "nice bathroom" → "walk-in shower with rainfall head and heated floors"</li>
            <li>Instead of "good natural light" → "south-facing windows that stay bright all afternoon"</li>
            <li>Instead of "parking available" → "dedicated covered parking spot included in rent"</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>5. Address objections before they arise</h2>
        <p>
            Prospective tenants have a mental checklist of deal-breakers. If your listing doesn't address them, they move on. Common ones include:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Pet policy — state it clearly upfront</li>
            <li>Laundry — in-unit, in-building, or nearest laundromat?</li>
            <li>Parking — included, street, or paid?</li>
            <li>Utilities — which are included in rent?</li>
            <li>Lease length — 12 months, 6 months, month-to-month?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            The more questions your listing answers, the higher quality your inquiries will be — because only genuinely interested tenants will reach out.
        </p>

        <h2>6. Stay Fair Housing compliant</h2>
        <p>
            The Fair Housing Act prohibits listings that express preference or limitation based on race, color, religion, sex, national origin, disability, or familial status. Violations can be unintentional — phrases like "perfect for a single professional" or "great for couples" can cross the line.
        </p>
        <p>
            Before publishing, review your listing for any language that implies a preferred tenant type. Stick to describing the property, not the ideal resident.
        </p>

        <h2>7. End with a clear call to action</h2>
        <p>
            Too many listings end with the rent amount and nothing else. Tell the tenant exactly what to do next: "Schedule a tour using the link below," "Text us to set up a showing," or "Apply directly at [URL]."
        </p>
        <p>
            A specific CTA reduces friction and increases the number of qualified inquiries you receive.
        </p>

        <div class="article-cta">
            <h3>Skip the blank page entirely.</h3>
            <p>DwellScript generates a complete, Fair Housing compliant rental listing in ~15 seconds. Free to start.</p>
            <a href="/Auth/Login"><i class="bi bi-stars"></i>Try DwellScript Free</a>
        </div>

        <h2>The bottom line</h2>
        <p>
            A great rental listing isn't about writing talent — it's about structure, specificity, and understanding what your prospective tenant is actually looking for. Lead with lifestyle, be specific about features, answer objections, and end with a clear next step.
        </p>
        <p>
            Do those four things consistently, and your vacancy periods will get shorter.
        </p>

